Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-09-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
I'm sorry, it looks like there already is question about it, but it remains unanswered, so I ask here. When I change the default 'Complete Deletion'\xA0 option to\xA0 'Pairwise Deletion' , I get 12 bootstrap-supported nodes instead of 10, and if I compute condensed trees (merge unreliable branchings) tree still looks better (except for (mis)placing Arabidopsis in the middle of P. marinus clade) So I wonder if 'Pairwise Deletion' is usually better, or only under certain circumstances (e.g. more gaps)?\xA0
Upvotes:
0
I am no expert on this, but I'd think that if you have very divergent sequences, you are going to end up with gaps in many different places, especially between organisms that would be far apart on the evolutionary tree. If you delete all of those positions, you are going to lose a lot of information. Gaps are likely to be in the same position in closely related species. Deleting them in pairwise comparison is then not going to lead to so much loss of information, especially between the closely related species. Less loss of information would probably lead to better overall statistics, i.e. higher scoring nodes.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
If you are aligning a lot of closely related sequences, you will get alignments where the gaps are in more or less the same positions. If you are aligning a lot of distantly related sequences, there may be gaps in more random locations. According to the MEGA manual: Pairwise deletion is relevant if the number of nucleotides involved in a gap is small and if the gaps are distributed more or less randomly . So I think pairwise deletion would be a better option for distantly related sequences.

Input.threadtitle: Lab4 Step 12 question a&b aren't addressed in Week 4 Discussion video !?
Input.posts:
Hello, Lab4 Step 12 questions a&b don't seem to be addressed in Week 4 Discussion video. Does anyone have the answers to questions a&b ? Thanks !
Upvotes:
0
Hi Kenneth Regarding question b perhaps since there is an overabundance of codons so a particular aminoacid could be obtained by several codons and some times the third codon change but still you get the same aminoacid, as we can see in the image below, that might introduce too much variation in the analysis. In the Criscuolo and Mechel article (link: http://dpt-info.u-strasbg.fr/~c.michel/Michel_Article44.pdf ) they propose a method to obtain a distance matrix based on codon alignment. They talk about eliminating the third codon because it induce fast evolutionary rate. http://dpt-info.u-strasbg.fr/~c.michel/Michel_Article44.pdf
Upvotes:
2
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Kenneth, I show 3 trees in the Lab Discussion, with different parameters. You can see that the bootstrap scores are pretty bad in the one on the right. Re. 3rd position of codons, Monica has it right: sometime there might be too much variation to get good bootstrap scores if you include the 3rd position. Non-coding sequences also tend to evolve faster therefore making it harder to get good bootstrap values. Best, Nick

Hello, Lab4 Step 12 questions a&b don't seem to be addressed in Week 4 Discussion video. Does anyone have the answers to questions a&b ? Thanks !
Upvotes:
0
Hi Kenneth Regarding question b perhaps since there is an overabundance of codons so a particular aminoacid could be obtained by several codons and some times the third codon change but still you get the same aminoacid, as we can see in the image below, that might introduce too much variation in the analysis. In the Criscuolo and Mechel article (link: http://dpt-info.u-strasbg.fr/~c.michel/Michel_Article44.pdf ) they propose a method to obtain a distance matrix based on codon alignment. They talk about eliminating the third codon because it induce fast evolutionary rate. http://dpt-info.u-strasbg.fr/~c.michel/Michel_Article44.pdf
Upvotes:
2
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hi Kenneth, I show 3 trees in the Lab Discussion, with different parameters. You can see that the bootstrap scores are pretty bad in the one on the right. Re. 3rd position of codons, Monica has it right: sometime there might be too much variation to get good bootstrap scores if you include the 3rd position. Non-coding sequences also tend to evolve faster therefore making it harder to get good bootstrap values. Best, Nick

Input.posts:
In Lab 4, Box 7, it says that '...this may be indicative of a partial or whole genome duplication event...' What is a genome duplication event? Is is a bifurcation point on a phylogenetic tree? Then, in Tree (3), Box 7,\xA0 what is the difference of a node marked by 'x2' and other nodes on this tree? Thank you.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Eduard, a whole genome duplication (WGD) event occurs when an organism is created with additional copies of its entire genome.\xA0 Perhaps a resource such as: http://genomevolution.org/wiki/index.php/Whole_genome_duplication may help to explain this further. The node marked 'x2' could indicate such an event as both Gene X (the original gene) and Gene Y (its paralog) exist in the Species A.

Input.posts:
Hi All I downloaded the latest version of MEGA (MEGA6) and the tree it generated was not what expected in the quiz... For example, the node number I got was not displayed in the choices (and the closest one was not correct either)... Since the first session quiz is coming, I am wondering whether any other people have met the same issue? Do I have to use MEGA5 in order to take the quiz? Thanks! =============================================================================== Problem Solved Thank Njin-Zu Chen for the idea. The key thing here is to use the BEST alignment from last week. I re-aligned the sequences with the right setting (gap open penalty 20) and repeated generating the tree. Both Q2 and Q3 make sense to me now.\xA0 FYI, I am still using MEGA6, so the version should not matter.
